%FEATURE_STRUCTURES.sofaString:
﻿The   patient   with   a   presumptive   diagnosis   of   Silver-
Russell  syndrome  was  first  referred  to  our  department  at 
7.5  years  of  age  due  to  severe  short  stature  since  infancy. 
His  past  medical  history  revealed  a  term  birth  weighing 
2250  g  [standard  deviation  (SD)  score    –  2.02],  no  chronic 
disease, being able to talk and walk by the age of 2.5 years
and  has  normal  intelligence.  His  parents  were  offsprings 
of  brothers.  His  healthy  brother  and  sister  had  normal 
stature, while the height of his mother was 155 cm and this
father, 170 cm. However, the reported height of the father
of the patient ’ s grandfather was 145 cm.
 Physical  examination  at  7.5  years  of  age  revealed  a 
height  of  95  cm  (SD  score    –  5.64),  a  weight  of  12.7  kg  (SD 
score  – 5.57), a triangular face, a low nasal bridge, a pectus
carinatum,  and  with  clinodactyly.  The  laboratory  studies 
showed  normal  biochemistry,  bone  age  consistent  with 
3  years  and  3  months,  IGF-1  87  ng/mL  (SD  score    –  0.98), 
IGFBP-3 2421 ng/mL (SD score  – 0.61), peak growth hormone
with  insulin  tolerance  test  after  hypoglycemia  32  mIU/mL 
(normal, >25 mIU/mL), and a normal 46, XY  karyotype. The
skeletal  survey  was  reported  to  show  J  sella  and  hyperlor-
dosis.  Although  a  definitive  diagnosis  could  not  be  made 
during the irregular follow-up, the clinical picture was not
considered to be consistent with Silver-Russell syndrome.
 Physical  examination  at  the  age  of  16  and  a  half 
revealed a height of 128.5 cm (SD score  – 5.27), weight 26 kg
(SD  score    –  7.26),  prominent  forehead,  anteverted  nasal 
openings, fleshy  nasal  tip,  full  lips,  malar  hypoplasia, 
hyperlordosis,  prominent  heels,  testicular  volumes  8  –  10 
mL, and pubic hair consistent with Tanner stage II (Figure
1  ). Follicle stimulating hormone (6.33 mIU/mL), luteinizing
hormone (1.64 mIU/mL), and total testosterone (347 ng/dL)
levels  were  in  normal  ranges.  A  trial  of  growth  hormone 
(0.2   mg/kg/week)   was   started   following   demonstrat-
ing  a  bone  age  consistent  with  14  years,  moderately  low 
peak  growth  hormone  during  hypoglycemia  (6.14  ng/mL; 
normal,   > 10  ng/mL),  and  adequate  rise  in  IGF-1  [from 
402 ng/mL (SD score 0.37) to 742 ng/mL, ΔIGF-1 340 ng/mL,
normal   > 20  ng/mL]  and  IGFBP-3  [from  5510  ng/mL  (SD 
score  1.3)  to  6580  ng/mL,   Δ IGFBP3  1070  ng/mL,  normal  > 400  ng/mL]  levels  with  IGF-1  generation  test.  However, the  growth  hormone  treatment  was  discontinued  due  to 
inadequate height gain (3 cm) by the end of 1 year.
At that time, a clinical diagnosis of 3-M syndrome was
made  upon  the  detection  of  unfamiliar  typical  findings 
(slender long bones and tall lumbar vertebrae) in a recent
skeletal  survey  (Figure    2    ).  The  indexes  proposed  by  van 
der  Wal  et  al.  were  calculated  in  our  patient:  the  stand-
ard  deviation  scores  of  metacarpal  index  were  in  normal 
ranges, however, vertebral index of the lumbar vertebrae
revealed  tall/foreshortened  vertebrae  (SD  scores  of  T12,
Demir et al.: Severe short stature due to 3-M syndrome
149 L1, L2, and L3: 2.24, 4.9, 3, and 2.44, respectively) consist-
ent with the diagnosis  (8) .
The mutation analyses of the patient and the parents
were  performed  in  the  Department  of  Genetics,  Paris 
Descartes  University.  First,  the   CUL7  gene  was  screened, 
and no mutation was found. Afterwards,  the
OBSL1  gene was studied, and a homozygote frame shift mutation was
found in exon 2: c.457_458delinsT resulting in p.Gly153fs.
The parents were heterozygous for the same mutation.
